{
  "query": "What are the potential negative impacts of different seeding strategies on existing native vegetation in North American grasslands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Different seeding strategies in North American grasslands can have several negative impacts on existing native vegetation. When sowing grass seeds specifically, studies have documented reduced abundance of native forb species and reduced abundance of shrub species. One replicated, randomized, paired, controlled study in Hungary found that sowing grass seeds reduced the abundance of grassland species. Additionally, three of four replicated studies found that sowing grass seeds either reduced native grass cover or did not alter native grass density, and two studies found it reduced the abundance of native forb species. Research on sowing native grass and forb seeds showed that while some studies found increased species richness initially, after 3-13 years, species richness did not differ between sown and unsown areas or was lower in sown areas compared to unsown areas. Furthermore, three studies found that species richness was lower in sown areas than in nearby intact grasslands when using native seed mixes. These findings suggest that various seeding approaches, whether using native or non-native species, can potentially suppress existing native vegetation through competition and may not maintain long-term species richness comparable to intact grassland communities.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3397",
    "3432"
  ]
}

