{
  "query": "What is the available evidence on the effectiveness of using nurse plants to improve grassland plant community composition and richness?",
  "relevant_summary": "The available evidence on nurse plants for grassland restoration shows mixed effectiveness for improving plant community composition and richness. For sowing nurse plant seeds alone (action 3401), one replicated, controlled study in France found that this practice reduced similarity of the plant community to nearby intact steppe compared to unsown areas, did not change plant species richness or vegetation cover, and resulted in lower richness than intact steppe. When nurse plants were sown alongside grassland species (action 3402), four studies (two in Europe, one in USA, one in Kenya) showed similar patterns: one study found reduced similarity to target community composition when nurse species were included in seed mixes, while another found no increase in species richness compared to mixes without nurse species. For vegetation abundance, one USA study found no change in grass or forb abundance when nurse plants were sown alongside grassland species. However, there were some positive effects on plant establishment: one Spanish study found increased seed germination when sown under nurse plants, and two studies (Kenya and Spain) showed variable effects on survival - one found increased survival of planted plants under nurse plants, while another found initial increases in seedling survival but no difference after 2-3 years.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3401",
    "3402"
  ]
}

