{
  "query": "In European grassland restoration, what are the benefits and drawbacks of sowing non-native grass seeds versus seeds from a local source?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence from European grassland restoration shows that sowing seeds from local sources has several benefits compared to using non-native seeds. Studies found that local seed sources increased plant species richness compared to commercial seed mixes (Action ID: 3400), and when combined with increased species diversity in seed mixes, led to increased species richness and cover of target plant species (Action ID: 3400, 3406). Local seed sources were also found to maintain or increase vegetation cover over time compared to areas sown with non-native seeds (Action ID: 3400). The evidence indicates that grasslands established with local seed sources developed communities more similar to those of intact grasslands over time (Action ID: 3397). While specific drawbacks of non-native seeds are not extensively detailed in the available evidence, the data suggests that commercial seed mixes and non-native sources generally resulted in lower plant species richness and did not achieve the same restoration outcomes as local seed sources (Action ID: 3400).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3400",
    "3406",
    "3397"
